mme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "National Climate Fund Case Study Report: Micronesian Conservation Trust", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-micronesian-conservation-trust", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "469767981bd62961b35a1e811836e2da3ed014cd28e590c3ea55eb53305f434a"}, "3": {"node_id": "39c40a20-2d92-446d-bf14-dcc8e4f98c19", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-micronesian-conservation-trust", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "2b3d20e8b7b881d4474fa6f9df9e03c54c311e4d64a40265021c96350e283477"}}, "hash": "c2eb2b40d36588524ee77eae93318a9b5162483fc35aa662f3806e85ff0f3608", "text": "Micronesian Conservation Trust A case study providing inputs to discussions in Asia-Pacific region on the design and management of National Climate Funds, jointly pepared by TNC, UNDP and MCT. Case Study Report: 2 Case Study Report: Micronesian Conservation Trust Table of Contents Introduction ........................................................................................................................................................................................... 3 The design of the MCT at a Glance ......................................................................................................................................................... 4 The role of the MCT in financing conservation in Federated States of Micronesia (FSM) .................................................................... 4 The legal status .................................................................................................................................................................................. 4 The model: different types of funds ................................................................................................................................................... 4 Governing body and beneficiaries ...................................................................................................................................................... 6 Fiduciary standards ............................................................................................................................................................................ 7 The establishment of the MCT ............................................................................................................................................................... 8 The political and legal process ............................................................................................................................................................ 8 The evolution of the MCT: from the national to subregional level ....................................................................................................... 9 The management of the MCT ................................................................................................................................................................ 9 The capacity of beneficiaries .............................................................................................................................................................. 9 The monitoring and evaluation system ............................................................................................................................................ 10 Risks mitigation ............................................................................................................................................................................... 11 Lessons-learned ................................................................................................................................................................................... 11 Stakeholder engagement and political enabling condition ............................................................................................................... 11 Fund Raising Capacity ...................................................................................................................................................................... 12 The advantage of a subregional fund in the Pacific ........................................................................................................................... 13 3 Case Study Report: Micronesian Conservation Trust Introduction This paper aims to enrich knowledge sharing about the establishment and management of national climate funds (NCFs), which is organized by the Asia-Pacific Community of Practice on Climate Finance. To provide a technical input to the knowledge sharing, UNDP commissioned seven case studies on existing national funds in the fields of environment, conservation, energy, climate change and development. This paper reports the lessons learned extracted from the establishment and management of the Micronesian Conservation Trust (MCT), which is one of seven national funds across the Asia-Pacific region selected as a case study1. The MCT is selected to provide an interesting case for countries in Asia-Pacific because of the following characteristics: 1. The structure of the MCT (the legal status of the MCT as a non-profit organization). The existing structure of the MCT allows for strong multi-stakeholders engagement with a Board of Trustees consisting of high-profiled and well-qualified people from Micronesian jurisdictions in the Federated States of Micronesia (FSM) as well as international members from outside the region. 2. The evolution of MCT. The most significant development in the growth and success of MCT has been its expansion beyond FSM to include in its programs the whole Micronesian Region by including the countries of Palau and the Marshall Islands as well as the United States territories of Guam and the Commonwealth of the Northern Mariana Islands. The scale of the MCT operations currently covers a total sea area of 6.7 million km2, representing more than 20% of the Pacific Island region and 5% of the largest ocean in the world. 3. The capacity to raise funds and manage different types of funds. The MCT\u2019s assets have been growing significantly over time. In 2004, the fund began with only US$ 50,000 of contribution from an anonymous donor. Currently, in 2012 the MCT\u2019s operating budget totals US$ 2.8 million, with a granting portfolio of US$ 1.8 million. The MCT currently manages several endowment funds and sinking funds. The MCT also provides financial services for other donors or funders to channel grants for intended beneficiaries through its intermediary granting. This report provides the summary of the overall design of the MCT and a short description about the process of the establishment and the management of the MCT. A brief analysis of the lessons-learned from the establishment and management of the MCT are then presented. The case study analysis involved: literature review to set the scope of the study and in-depth interviews with the Executive Director of the MCT.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "39c40a20-2d92-446d-bf14-dcc8e4f98c19": {"__data__": {"id_": "39c40a20-2d92-446d-bf14-dcc8e4f98c19", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-micronesian-conservation-trust", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "National Climate Fund Case Study Report: Micronesian Conservation Trust", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-micronesian-conservation-trust", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "469767981bd62961b35a1e811836e2da3ed014cd28e590c3ea55eb53305f434a"}, "2": {"node_id": "4c951550-629f-4537-98ca-3e85c64dad8f", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-micronesian-conservation-trust", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "c2eb2b40d36588524ee77eae93318a9b5162483fc35aa662f3806e85ff0f3608"}}, "hash": "2b3d20e8b7b881d4474fa6f9df9e03c54c311e4d64a40265021c96350e283477", "text": "1 National funds selected for the case study analysis are: Bhutan Trust Fund for Environmental Conservation, China CMD Fund, Cambodia Climate Change Alliance Trust Fund, Thailand Energy Conservation Promotion Fund, Lao Environmental Protection Fund, Micronesian Conservation Trust and Tuvalu Trust Fund 4 Case Study Report: Micronesian Conservation Trust The design of the MCT at a Glance The role of the MCT in financing conservation in Federated States of Micronesia (FSM) MCT is the region\u2019s only conservation trust fund, and is one of the key regional, international, and US Federal agencies and organizations, that together form the Regional Support Team (RST)2. The RST was pulled together to provide a higher level of support for the Micronesia Challenge, a once-in-a-generation opportunity to significantly \u201cramp up\u201d biodiversity conservation and climate change adaptation efforts in Micronesia. In 2006, the MCT was selected as the financial mechanism for the Micronesia Challenge Initiative and has since fully regionalized its organizational structure and services including its programs for the whole Micronesian Region (i.e. Palau and the Marshall Islands as well as", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "ffc9a6a0-d387-490e-be97-be3d1ef63bf5": {"__data__": {"id_": "ffc9a6a0-d387-490e-be97-be3d1ef63bf5", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-micronesian-conservation-trust", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "National Climate Fund Case Study Report: Micronesian Conservation Trust", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-micronesian-conservation-trust", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "ba08c4ac4a9733257ab814e45be4aef0c18abeac6acc8e4029fe786d6d7bb700"}, "3": {"node_id": "42b7b3b1-d776-4a30-8773-2c492e30da74", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-micronesian-conservation-trust", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "48984a83027e61025104bef42c344f8864bfc3b32a3bc4baafca94c8778441ae"}}, "hash": "c6fddda87eb44eec8ecad84ee41e6a01cd70f569139d80a9b2f4bf141c4603ae", "text": "the United States territories of Guam and the Commonwealth of the Northern Mariana Islands). The Micronesia Challenge Initiative is a high-level commitment made by the Chief Executives of each of the five Micronesian jurisdictions (Republic of Palau, FSM, Republic of the Marshall Islands, the Commonwealth of the Northern Mariana Islands and Guam) to effectively conserve at least 30% of near-shore marine and 20% of the terrestrial resources across Micronesia by 20203. In its role as the financial mechanism of the Micronesia Challenge Initiative, MCT assists the MC jurisdictions raise, invest, disburse and manage the Micronesia Challenge Endowment Fund, as well as other sinking funds towards MC\u2019s ongoing activities. The legal status The MCT aims to manage and provide funds for the accomplishment of its mission: \u201cto support biodiversity conservation and related sustainable development for the people of Micronesia by providing long term sustained funding.\u201d The MCT was granted as a Non-Profit Corporation Charter by the President of the Federated States of Micronesia in November 2002. Subsequently, the MCT obtained its registration as nonprofit corporation in the Federated States of Micronesia, through a Registry Certificate issued by the Federated States of Micronesia Registrar of Corporations, based on its corresponding Articles of Incorporation and Bylaws. The MCT adheres to policies and standards set out in its Articles of Incorporation, By-Laws and Operations Manual as duly adopted and approved under the laws of the Federated States of Micronesia. The model: different types of funds The MCT currently manages two different types of funds: a set of endowment funds and advised sinking funds, which are both used to support the annual operation and direct grantmaking program. Currently, the MCT provides grants (known as a direct grant making program) that are funded through a variety of sinking funds and will eventually be financed by sustainable revenue provided by MCT\u2019s Endowment Fund. Each of these funds is discussed below. 2 Key partners of the RST include: The Nature Conservancy (TNC), Conservation International (CI), the Secretariat of the Pacific Regional Environment Programme (SPREP), RARE International, Palau International Coral Reef Center (PICRC), Global Island Partnership (GLISPA), Pacific Marine Resources Institute (PMRI), Locally Managed Marine Area (LMMA) Network, Pacific Islands Forum Secretariat (PIFS), the Secretariat of the Pacific Community (SPC), United Nations Environment Programme (UNEP), US National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA), the US Environment Protection Agency (USEPA), the US Forest Service (USFS), the US Department of Interior, Office of Insular Affairs (OIA), and the local conservation NGOs in each island. 3 Remengseau T. Presentation by the President of the Republic of Palau at the 9th Conference of the Parties to the Convention on Biological Diversity, Bonn, Germany, May 2008. Cited by Rose, Justin. \u201cMicronesia Converation Trust: Securing Finances for Micronesia\u2019s Biodiversity Conservation and Sustainable Development\u201d, University of New England. 2008 5 Case Study Report: Micronesian Conservation Trust Endowment funds - The MCT currently manages three endowment funds, namely the MCT Endowment Fund, the Micronesia Challenge Endowment Fund and the Yela Conservation Easement Endowment Fund. These funds provide ongoing support to the MCT\u2019s annual operations and direct grantmaking program, as well as to the operations of the Micronesia Challenge and the Yela Conservation Easement\u2019s initiatives. As of March 31, 2012 the total endowment funds that MCT managed through Endowment Funds was approximately US$ 11.2 million. The endowment for the regional Micronesia Challenge Initiative currently totals US$ 10.5 million out of the total pledge of US$ 11.1 million from a GEF project (US$ 6 million), The Nature Conservancy (US$ 3 million), the Government of Palau (US$ 1.9 million), and the Government of RMI (US$ 200,000). In addition, the Yela Conservation Easement initiative and the MCT Endowment Fund amount to US$ 500,000 and US$ 200,000 (Table 1). The MCT Board of Trustees defines a spending policy for the MCT Endowment Fund to determine annual funding available for granting or for adding up the total endowment funds invested.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "42b7b3b1-d776-4a30-8773-2c492e30da74": {"__data__": {"id_": "42b7b3b1-d776-4a30-8773-2c492e30da74", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-micronesian-conservation-trust", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "National Climate Fund Case Study Report: Micronesian Conservation Trust", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-micronesian-conservation-trust", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "ba08c4ac4a9733257ab814e45be4aef0c18abeac6acc8e4029fe786d6d7bb700"}, "2": {"node_id": "ffc9a6a0-d387-490e-be97-be3d1ef63bf5", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-micronesian-conservation-trust", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "c6fddda87eb44eec8ecad84ee41e6a01cd70f569139d80a9b2f4bf141c4603ae"}}, "hash": "48984a83027e61025104bef42c344f8864bfc3b32a3bc4baafca94c8778441ae", "text": "The MCT has the sole responsibility and authority for investment of the assets of each Fund, where the Board of Trustees decides about the retention, investment, or reinvestment of assets. An investment policy is developed by the Board of Trustees and implemented by the MCT Investment Committee with the assistance of an Investment Consultant and Advisor. The interests generated from the endowment funds have not been used to provide grants, but left in to build up the total endowment funds invested. This strategy is pursued to build up the capital so that it can generate sufficient interests or dividends to provide grants for conservation. Advised Sinking Funds \u2013 The MCT can also serve as an intermediary to donor partners and funders that", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "df045fc8-a799-4f24-a085-f95a71fffe9c": {"__data__": {"id_": "df045fc8-a799-4f24-a085-f95a71fffe9c", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-micronesian-conservation-trust", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "National Climate Fund Case Study Report: Micronesian Conservation Trust", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-micronesian-conservation-trust", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "21bc2a2f1bef54992c712d41dd6b1f67e7287a73add511292a31ba91a2a5c4e2"}, "3": {"node_id": "077a57f9-9ac0-4192-9e85-efa5d7015860", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-micronesian-conservation-trust", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "1dcbf562e9b36fe85b0ec1c271bd9727788154dee772190b1428c4d41e0cc7a4"}}, "hash": "1f5b4378e3a573a56766ee8c29e092ede7804bb08a23746d1e4cb0afb5218318", "text": "share MCT\u2019s mission of conservation in Micronesia and need assistance in their grantmaking. For this purpose, the MCT creates a new Advised Sinking Fund, which is an account managed in the MCT\u2019s accounting system for a specific granting purpose. The purpose of the MCT\u2019s sinking fund is to support MCT\u2019s grantmaking and operations over a predetermined timeframe. The use of the fund should be in compliance with an Intermediary/regranting agreement between the Board of Trustees of MCT and the donor. In contrast to the endowment fund, all sinking fund capital is used (for payments to cover project, administrative and other costs). The use of the sinking fund is determined by the MCT\u2019s proposal to respective donors and agreed in the contracts/agreements with the donors. The amount allocated for operations and for direct grantmaking is also determined by the contracts/agreements between MCT and the donors. The MCT has never received a donation and/or grant without agreed terms of the use of the fund. In the last four years the MCT management fee is an average of less than 20 percent. For example, in 2011, the MCT\u2019s management fee was at 16 percent with the remaining amount is spent for providing grants to its implementing partners (Table 1). Over the past five years, MCT has managed several \u2018advised funds\u2019 and re-granted resources to relevant conservation community projects. These include funds from donors such as: the German Ministry of Environment, US Department of Interior, US NOAA, the Non- State Actors Funds from the European Union\u2019s Economic Development Fund (EDF9) to the FSM, alongside funds from other foreign governments and private foundations. Finally, the MCT also received and secured Climate Change Adaptation funds from German ICI, Australian Government and other private donors to begin putting a climate lens on protected areas management plans, as well as support for on the ground adaptation activities. 6 Case Study Report: Micronesian Conservation Trust Table 1. The MCT\u2019s Portfolio as of 2012 As of 2012 Total Usage \u2013 for operation Usage \u2013 for granting Endowment Funds Total endowment: US$ 11.2 million Total annual interest since the inception: US$ 1.7 million US$ 0/year US$ 0/year Advised Sinking Funds Total donations received for Advised Sinking Funds: US$ 7 million (+) Management fee: 16 percent (on average) Grants: 84 percent (on average) Governing body and beneficiaries The MCT\u2019s governing structure, which has remained mostly the same since its inception, is composed by: \uf0b7 A Board of Trustees who makes all policy decisions and provides final approval for grants and disbursement of interest made from our endowments. The board of members consists of 7 Regional Members who all live in Micronesia (Palau, Guam, CNMI, FSM and the Marshall Islands) and 2 International Members (currently one from Japan and one from USA). There is also an ex- officio (non-voting) Board member from The Nature Conservancy, who is a major donor to the Micronesia Challenge Endowment Fund. It is a self-selecting Board and members are selected based on their expertise, contributions and commitment to Micronesia\u2019s (sustainable) development. Each Board Member must be nominated based on their contributions to science, conservation, sustainable development and their overall commitment to the Micronesia Sub-region. Each term is for three years and individual Board Members have the possibility of serving an additional three-year term if nominated and re- confirmed by the existing Board. The role in overseeing the management office of the MCT involves setting policies such as Strategic Action Plans and Grantmaking Strategies, approving budgets and grants, supporting fundraising efforts, and selection of the Executive Director. \uf0b7 A Technical Project Review Committee, chaired by one of the board members, who is a scientist. The technical committee members are scientists/experts selected from across the region (Australia, Hawaii and Micronesia). Their expertise ranges from social sciences to biodiversity conservation, climate change, invasive species, and others. \uf0b7 The Executive Director (ED) leads the management office of MCT with currently seven other staff (as of June 2012). The ED was selected by the Board of Trustees and is be responsible for oversight of administration and financial management of MCT and its budget, including the day-to-day operations of the Trust.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "077a57f9-9ac0-4192-9e85-efa5d7015860": {"__data__": {"id_": "077a57f9-9ac0-4192-9e85-efa5d7015860", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-micronesian-conservation-trust", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "National Climate Fund Case Study Report: Micronesian Conservation Trust", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-micronesian-conservation-trust", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "21bc2a2f1bef54992c712d41dd6b1f67e7287a73add511292a31ba91a2a5c4e2"}, "2": {"node_id": "df045fc8-a799-4f24-a085-f95a71fffe9c", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-micronesian-conservation-trust", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "1f5b4378e3a573a56766ee8c29e092ede7804bb08a23746d1e4cb0afb5218318"}}, "hash": "1dcbf562e9b36fe85b0ec1c271bd9727788154dee772190b1428c4d41e0cc7a4", "text": "The responsibilities of the ED include: 1) developing and implementing strategies to secure funding for MCT endowment funds; 2) developing and managing of annual budget, including producing income and expense report; 3) identifying, planning, and designing the financing programs to provide sustainable, long-term resources for the MCT in close coordination with the MCT Board of Directors and Technical Advisors; 4) guiding the development of and direct implementation of capital fundraising drives; and 5) implementing MCT\u2019s grantmaking and capacity- building activities. \uf0b7", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "b65a8cb4-c191-497e-b885-07ea72612714": {"__data__": {"id_": "b65a8cb4-c191-497e-b885-07ea72612714", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-micronesian-conservation-trust", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "National Climate Fund Case Study Report: Micronesian Conservation Trust", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-micronesian-conservation-trust", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "0328f92a6633a6246b302f0ed0a84f1912a015bffc0f065f1d6fb3699d019ed6"}}, "hash": "0328f92a6633a6246b302f0ed0a84f1912a015bffc0f065f1d6fb3699d019ed6", "text": "The Investment Committee is primarily responsible to oversee the management of MCT\u2019s financial assets of with MCT\u2019s investment policy. The Chairperson will convene at least quarterly meetings of the Committee to review the Investment portfolio performance in accordance with MCT investment goals and recommend changes if necessary. The Committee will also provide a semi-annual report to the Board of Trustees on the performance of the investment portfolio. The Board of Trustees appoints the members of the Investment Committee and the Chairperson of the Investment Committee is drawn from the membership of the Board of Trustees. The Committee shall consist of at least three people with an investment or finance 7 Case Study Report: Micronesian Conservation Trust background. The term of service of Investment Committee members is three years with the potential to renew the position to only a second term. The MCT currently implements two grant-making programs: direct grant-making program and intermediary grant-making program. The direct grant-making program is currently funded through a variety of sinking funds and will eventually be financed by sustainable revenue provided by MCT\u2019s Endowment Fund. The two different grants provided under the direct grant-making program are4: \uf0b7 Project grants to a specific program or initiative undertaken by an individual organization or a group of organizations. MCT awards grants to government and nongovernmental organizations for projects related to the protection and management of targeted marine and terrestrial areas. These projects include direct management activities, e.g. monitoring and evaluation work, support of alternative economic activities to replace unsustainable practices, and related public awareness strategies to inform and gain support from community members. \uf0b7 Capacity Building Grants to increase the capacity of organizations. MCT\u2019s conservation outcomes are also achieved through its capacity building programs. These include two peer learning networks (Micronesians in Island Conservation and Pacific Islands Managed and Protected Areas Community) coordinated by MCT and designed to strengthen leadership, increase knowledge, experience and skills, and catalyze regional collaborations. MCT capacity building also includes grants for technical assistance and training to grantee organizations to strengthen their ability to successfully achieve conservation goals. With the intermediary grant-making program, the MCT also serves as an intermediary to other foundations and donors who need assistance in their grant-making to the Micronesia Region. The MCT provides assistance through the re-granting of their funds to appropriate conservation organizations and projects that share MCT\u2019s mission of conservation and climate adaptation in Micronesia. For project selection, the MCT issues a call for proposals approved by the board. Once project proposals are received, the management staff will assess them to ensure all the criteria and requested information and supporting documents are met by project proponents. Direct grant-making projects that meet all the requirements are provided to the Technical Project Review Committee for their reviews and comments. Their comments are compiled and shared to the Board of Trustees to help the board make final approval and/or disapproval of projects. In some cases, the board will allow the project proponent to improve their project proposal for further consideration. With intermediary grant-making projects, the MCT works with donors and the grantees to determine the specific terms of contracts and activities. Once the projects are approved, the Executive staff carries out a due diligence exercise to make sure the project proponent can manage the project funds with prudence. The MCT looks at their accounting systems and internal controls, as well as their project management capabilities. The organizations\u2019 audit reports are sometime required depending on the level of funding provided. Fiduciary standards The MCT follows the Generally Accepted Auditing Principles maintained by the Financial Accounting Standards Board, widely followed and recognized in the United States. The MCT also commissions independent financial audits. In lieu of an official audit committee, MCT outlines in detail the fiduciary responsibilities of the Board of Directors in the Bylaws. For its accounting work, MCT has among its staff a Finance Officer who prepares all the financial reports, such as the Financial 4 Micronesia Conservation Trust Annual Report of the Micronesia Conservation Trust (Pohnpei, Micronesia Conservation Trust, 2008); Micronesia Conservation Trust Annual Report of the Micronesia Conservation Trust (Pohnpei, Micronesia Conservation Trust, 2010) 8 Case Study Report: Micronesian Conservation Trust Statements previously indicated, and maintains MCT\u2019s Chart of Accounts, which lists each account that the accounting system tracks. It is designed to enable MCT to capture the financial information that the Executive Secretariat and the Board need to keep track of all financial data and to make informed financial decisions. It is important to note that these financial reports are regularly reviewed by the Executive Secretariat and the MCT Board Treasurer who is a licensed", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "01d92780-4e5b-405c-8168-309ad777a7ff": {"__data__": {"id_": "01d92780-4e5b-405c-8168-309ad777a7ff", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-micronesian-conservation-trust", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "National Climate Fund Case Study Report: Micronesian Conservation Trust", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-micronesian-conservation-trust", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "8bd4563d2083c28b9cc44a4e589149895e61c4e4abb39daf1de69ce99ed94c0c"}, "3": {"node_id": "4efa4746-3323-4410-ad4c-2354ee5f3655", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-micronesian-conservation-trust", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "8ca88fa84626f837e21d27fc30ce0534bf1b1924235e4057d02d32b6d4693c84"}}, "hash": "ca846dfb5a60f5af250ea365ff3cefcec1927cc99f273c1c5cae32902fe51a2c", "text": "US Certified Public Accountant (CPA) and that these reports are reviewed on a quarterly basis by the full board. These systems allow MCT to conduct its accounting processes in accordance with high level accounting standards in order to efficiently and transparently track both restricted and non-restricted donations and grants, and performing the functional classification of expenses and income. The establishment of the MCT The political and legal process The establishment of the MCT was initiated during the first meeting of the group that was to become the MCT steering committee. The meeting, held in Chuuk State in 2001, was attended by seventeen people representing various organizations and conservation-related interests from FSM\u2019s four states. The meeting was to decide whether there was sufficient interest in establishing a Conservation Trust Fund (CTF) in FSM, and if so to determine the next steps and how to overcome any identified challenges. The major outcome of the Chuuk meeting was unanimous support for a CTF in FSM and the group constituted itself as a steering committee mandated to achieve that purpose5. The establishment of the MCT was initiated around the same time with the negotiations for the renewal of The Compact of Free Association between FSM and the United States of America (the Compact). The \u2018environment\u2019 was considered as an additional sector for the renegotiated Compact both alleviated much concern regarding future environmental protection in FSM. This was crucial in terms of generating sufficient interest among the relevant stakeholders in coming together to discuss establishing a CTF such as the MCT. The strategy and the hope among environment stakeholders at that time was that the FSM National Government would agree to allocate a portion of the environment sector Compact funds towards a CTF. However, ultimately that strategy proved fruitless in that the FSM Government decided not to include a CTF in their package of requests, leaving MCT in a difficult position6. In early 2004, the MCT could only raise less than US $100,000. At the July 2004 Board meeting it was reported to the Board of Trustees that MCT had sufficient funds to operate only until October of that year7. At that time the necessary shift in strategy was decided. \u2018MCT needed to demonstrate what a CTF is; how this mechanism actually works on the ground. We decided to forget the Compact idea and focus on implementing a small pilot grant program to showcase the usefulness of MCT to stakeholders in FSM and to external donors\u20198. In its early phase of operation the reluctance of the FSM National Government to provide anything other than verbal support for MCT was clearly an inhibiting factor. The efforts to establish the MCT took about 3 years since stakeholder consultations and expert scoping analysis started early in 2000 until the end of 2002 when it got chartered and registered before the FSM Government\u2019s agencies. Much of the transaction costs in the 5 The Nature Conservancy, Report of the First Meeting of the Steering Committee for a Conservation Trust Fund in the Federated States Of Micronesia, Chuuk, 2001.Cited by Rose, J. \u201cThe Micronesia Conservation Trust\u201d, pg. 15 6 Rose, J. \u201cThe Micronesia Conservation Trust\u201d, pgs. 12-13 7 Micronesia Conservation Trust Minutes of Board Meeting, Pohnpei, July 2004.Cited by Rose, J. \u201cThe Micronesia Conservation Trust\u201d, pg. 18 8 Cantin E, Advisor on Trust Funds, The Nature Conservancy, Personal Communication, November 2008. Cited by Rose, J. \u201cThe Micronesia Conservation Trust\u201d, pg. 18 9 Case Study Report: Micronesian Conservation Trust early stages of establishing the MCT were absorbed by multiple partners. As an example, TNC was instrumental in the establishment of the MCT from the earliest stages through to its maturation, facilitating much of the initial planning and consultative activity around establishing a CTF in FSM. TNC initial investment was approximately $400,000 and it supported the development of the organization (i.e. governance structure, which included development of necessary documents to enable its incorporation with the Federated States of Micronesia).", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "4efa4746-3323-4410-ad4c-2354ee5f3655": {"__data__": {"id_": "4efa4746-3323-4410-ad4c-2354ee5f3655", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-micronesian-conservation-trust", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "National Climate Fund Case Study Report: Micronesian Conservation Trust", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-micronesian-conservation-trust", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "8bd4563d2083c28b9cc44a4e589149895e61c4e4abb39daf1de69ce99ed94c0c"}, "2": {"node_id": "01d92780-4e5b-405c-8168-309ad777a7ff", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-micronesian-conservation-trust", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "ca846dfb5a60f5af250ea365ff3cefcec1927cc99f273c1c5cae32902fe51a2c"}}, "hash": "8ca88fa84626f837e21d27fc30ce0534bf1b1924235e4057d02d32b6d4693c84", "text": "The evolution of the MCT: from the national to subregional level The MCT Board of Trustees and management staff first began to envisage MCT as an organization performing a regional role beyond the four States of the FSM when it was offered the opportunity to coordinate the Pacific Islands Managed and Protected Areas Community (a program funded by the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration of the United States Government). Around the same time the MCT commenced discussions for hosting the GEF Small Grants Program covering FSM, the Marshall Islands and Palau, as well as a region-wide invasive species eradication project. These developments indicated that there is a demand for a trust fund", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "bbb2bc7f-2ab2-4a4e-b3a7-ba347db03ca9": {"__data__": {"id_": "bbb2bc7f-2ab2-4a4e-b3a7-ba347db03ca9", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-micronesian-conservation-trust", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "National Climate Fund Case Study Report: Micronesian Conservation Trust", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-micronesian-conservation-trust", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "fd1ca49ba7123b91faf367a141d36b67bbe42f68188696859314b907c449bd4a"}, "3": {"node_id": "4b116907-e8de-432b-9274-e2dbaeed0e60", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-micronesian-conservation-trust", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "872f13876aa383777c5c9882f41eb49810ab762abac34721e6ce04b6eb7ac960"}}, "hash": "366b14aba0afb311c15de3dea6e3e5f07c738a49c3cbb7ef07cca127c2bb7e6a", "text": "covering a broader geographic area was greater than a national trust fund for a country such as FSM with a population of only 110,0009. It was decided by the trustees that MCT\u2019s regionalization initiative should proceed following the revision of its By-Laws, Articles of Incorporation, the adoption of an Investment Policy and the appointment of an investment manager10. MCT\u2019s regionalization greatly assisted the emergence of the most important development in Micronesian conservation policy and governance, namely the Micronesia Challenge. The five Micronesian jurisdictions re-affirmed their commitment to the Micronesia Challenge at the Eighth Conference of the Parties to the Convention on Biological Diversity and have since put in place measures to oversee its implementation11. As previously discussed, the MCT was then appointed as the financing mechanism of the Micronesia Challenge. The MCT further signed a series of memoranda of understanding with the governments and administrations of the region\u2019s to ensure cooperation in developing guidelines and procedures for managing and disbursing the substantial Micronesia Challenge Endowment Fund. Under the agreements, the MCT will assist each country in developing country program strategies consistent with the broader regional strategy, including targets, milestones and measures to be achieved. Additionally, the agreements call on the MCT to work closely with the jurisdictions to develop sustainable financing plans and a business plan for the Micronesia Challenge. These agreements greatly assist in institutionalizing the Micronesia Challenge and providing detailed plans of action by which its goals shall be met12. The management of the MCT The capacity of beneficiaries Since 2004, the MCT has focused on capacity development of recipients to manage and implement projects. MCT performs this function through the Capacity-Building Program Manager (CBPM), who is solely responsible for the implementation and management of grants 9 Rose, J. \u201cThe Micronesia Conservation Trust\u201d, pg. 22 10 Ibid., loc. cit. 11 Killion R Statement by FSM Vice President on the Micronesia Challenge Initiative at the 8th Conference of the Parties to the Convention on Biological Diversity Curitiba, Brazil, 28 March 2006. Cited by Rose, J. \u201cThe Micronesia Conservation Trust\u201d, pg. 23 12 Rose, J. \u201cThe Micronesia Conservation Trust\u201d, pg. 23 10 Case Study Report: Micronesian Conservation Trust supporting MCT\u2019s capacity-building and peer learning network activities. The CBPM performs more formal needs and capacity assessments and arranges for training and learning exchanges and other activities to ensure that the needs are met. The CBPM also coordinates the two peer learning networks Micronesians in Island Conservation (MIC), whose aim is to support the development of conservation leaders and their organizations, and the Pacific Islands Managed and Protected Areas Community (PIMPAC), whose aim is to provide training and capacity building interventions to field conservation professionals across the Micronesia region. One other example that expresses MCT\u2019s extensive capability to build capacity of external partners and grantees on financial management and budgeting skills is the training workshop on how to use the accounting software QuickBooks Premiere Nonprofit, offered by MCT\u2019s Financial Officer. This training course provided guidance on how to use the software and also offers simpler systems for grantee partners without the need for highly sophisticated accounting system. By offering this course, MCT has established a capacity building platform around its accounting services that enhances the organizational capacity as well as the grantee partners\u2019. The monitoring and evaluation system Project monitoring activities are conducted by the Conservation Program Staff. The Conservation Program Manager assigns projects for monitoring to one of the two grants officers or retains responsibility for certain projects as appropriate. The assigned staff then assumes responsibility for the finalization of contract documents, workplans and reporting schedules and requirements in conjunction with the MCT Conservation Program Manager. The MCT staff then maintains regular contact with the project staff, issuing reminders of reports due, handling concerns, making referrals for technical assistance and advice as needed and others. The Conservation Program Staff also conducts regular site visits to monitor the progress of MCT funded projects. These occur at least quarterly, and sometimes as needed between regularly scheduled visits. The visits include a physical check of inventory purchased with grant materials, interviews with project staff and any community partners, including government technical support agencies and visits to actual project sites to observe work either underway or completed, participation in community meetings and other project related activities.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "4b116907-e8de-432b-9274-e2dbaeed0e60": {"__data__": {"id_": "4b116907-e8de-432b-9274-e2dbaeed0e60", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-micronesian-conservation-trust", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "National Climate Fund Case Study Report: Micronesian Conservation Trust", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-micronesian-conservation-trust", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "fd1ca49ba7123b91faf367a141d36b67bbe42f68188696859314b907c449bd4a"}, "2": {"node_id": "bbb2bc7f-2ab2-4a4e-b3a7-ba347db03ca9", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-micronesian-conservation-trust", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "366b14aba0afb311c15de3dea6e3e5f07c738a49c3cbb7ef07cca127c2bb7e6a"}}, "hash": "872f13876aa383777c5c9882f41eb49810ab762abac34721e6ce04b6eb7ac960", "text": "When the evaluation and monitoring exercises identify the needs for capacity development, MCT will help bring support through its two peer learning networks. Identified trainings are usually provided by an expert from within the two learning networks or from an outside expert if the expertise is not available within the two networks. Preference is given to the", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "fecb6009-55ce-4bbf-a4a9-62956360aeb8": {"__data__": {"id_": "fecb6009-55ce-4bbf-a4a9-62956360aeb8", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-micronesian-conservation-trust", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "National Climate Fund Case Study Report: Micronesian Conservation Trust", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-micronesian-conservation-trust", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "e93914d73763d127466a634ba5142e63655f19d7f08abaa64208bf60dd1a30c3"}, "3": {"node_id": "dd3fa1c9-c773-4931-98cd-8912914cc50c", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-micronesian-conservation-trust", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "a68e54708a791a7b9f056dc9c3080594621179f1e94cbcd7f2c38a03b6edc716"}}, "hash": "fce1f8511d2ea68af470216a08cdca387f2df329da593b80f8476709e22e3dd4", "text": "former to minimize costs. This capacity building support can include trainings ranging from organizational effectiveness to development of monitoring plans and exercises to project managers. Before capacity building activities (i.e. learning exchanges, technical assistance, mentoring, etc) take place, a form is filled out which describes the goals, objectives, expected outputs and outcomes for the training. The monitoring of the capacity building work are final reports submitted to the CBPM by both the trainer and the trainee. These state what happened, what was learned and how those contributed to the individual\u2019s or organization\u2019s development. These also include a description of how to sustain what has been learned. Both the pre-training and post training forms are signed by the trainee\u2019s supervisor(s). 11 Case Study Report: Micronesian Conservation Trust Risks mitigation The Deputy Executive Director is primarily responsible for conducting due diligence activities during the call for proposals process. For projects/grants over $10,000, the grantee needs to submit r\u00e9sum\u00e9s for the project coordinator/manager and other relevant staff, a history of prior grants from other funders and an annual report or other documents describing the organization\u2019s activities and accomplishments for the last two years are also required. The Finance Officer and the DED review the financial documents, while the Conservation Program Manager and Capacity-Building Program Manager provide input as to the proponent\u2019s technical and organizational capacity to carry out the project. MCT does not apply formal risk assessments because of the small size and closely-knit nature of the Micronesia conservation field. However, the MCT management team and other staff are aware of potential risks to project implementation, especially with regard to organizational and staff technical capacity, work-loads and commitments. Partner agencies and NGOs are aware of and share with MCT potential risks when community organizations are involved and assist with abating these threats. When it is determined that the project proponent (these are usually the community groups) does not have the capacity to manage the funds prudently MCT will request a fiscal sponsor (this role is usually carried out by a more established NGO for a fee). In addition, the MCT Regional Grants Technical Committee assesses project proposals for feasibility and also considers potential risks to the successful implementation of the proposed projects. This committee also is available for advice and guidance if and when a project encounters difficulties or challenges during project implementation and has served in the past to assist with the re-focusing of project activities and/or the scope of activities in order to achieve the desired project results. Lessons-learned Stakeholder engagement and political enabling condition Strong stakeholder engagement creates a basis for good governance during the establishment and the implementation of the MCT. During the setting up of the MCT, the planning and consultation process was conducted in a coordinated manner. \uf0b7 First, the planning and consultation process addressed the challenge of interstate competition over the MCT. This issue was addressed by establishing the MCT Board representation upon what was termed an \u201ceco-regional basis\u201d. Representation on the initial MCT Board would provide equity throughout the country by regarding the FSM not as divided between four States, but as \u2018high-islands\u2019 and \u2018low-islands\u2019 (atolls) each with different ecological and social issues and priorities13. \uf0b7 Second, the consultation and planning for MCT was undertaken at the same time as the FSM\u2019s National Biodiversity Strategy Action Plan (NBSAP) process. Many stakeholder consultation and planning meetings were conducted for the purpose of NBSAP preparation and these served as fora in which the nascent MCT could be introduced and described to key individuals and organizations concerned with biodiversity conservation in FSM. The FSM NBSAP identifies the MCT as the primary funding mechanism for many of its activities. Coordination between the development of the MCT along with the principle biodiversity 13 Ibid., pg. 16 12 Case Study Report: Micronesian Conservation Trust plans at State and National level ensured a detailed awareness in relation to environmental and conservation issues in FSM among a broad set of stakeholders14. The existing structure of the MCT as a non-profit organization allows for multi-stakeholder engagement. The members of the Board of the Trustee represent a selection of people from civil society conservation organizations. This structure is different to most national funds in Asia-Pacific where government representatives are the dominant members in the Board of the Trustee.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "dd3fa1c9-c773-4931-98cd-8912914cc50c": {"__data__": {"id_": "dd3fa1c9-c773-4931-98cd-8912914cc50c", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-micronesian-conservation-trust", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "National Climate Fund Case Study Report: Micronesian Conservation Trust", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-micronesian-conservation-trust", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "e93914d73763d127466a634ba5142e63655f19d7f08abaa64208bf60dd1a30c3"}, "2": {"node_id": "fecb6009-55ce-4bbf-a4a9-62956360aeb8", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-micronesian-conservation-trust", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "fce1f8511d2ea68af470216a08cdca387f2df329da593b80f8476709e22e3dd4"}}, "hash": "a68e54708a791a7b9f056dc9c3080594621179f1e94cbcd7f2c38a03b6edc716", "text": "Having a self-selecting Board structure in place, the MCT can, in most cases, stay out of the political landscape and avoid being swayed by political pressures, which provides MCT with the ability to select projects and programs based on their merit instead of political determinations. Additional advantages of having this structure in the Pacific Region", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "b83dbe6b-c902-4544-a426-eb664004b192": {"__data__": {"id_": "b83dbe6b-c902-4544-a426-eb664004b192", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-micronesian-conservation-trust", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "National Climate Fund Case Study Report: Micronesian Conservation Trust", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-micronesian-conservation-trust", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "0f18d7264f264b41825fc0e911d17e08b58b59d7b334301d3a175aa61c2e4822"}}, "hash": "0f18d7264f264b41825fc0e911d17e08b58b59d7b334301d3a175aa61c2e4822", "text": "include ensuring that the Board Members and staff selected are high-profiled individuals with great respect from donor agencies, technical partners, and stakeholders. A disadvantage to this structure may be that due to the self-selecting Board structure, some government leaders may have reservations about the lack of control they may have over the MCT. Fund Raising Capacity Instead of commencing operations with a large guaranteed funding source, the MCT had to operate from very limited resources. The MCT was forced, through circumstances not of its own choosing, to develop an incremental approach to fundraising has produced unforeseen benefits and strengths for the organization; those of a \u201cbottom up\u201d approach. Being forced to build upon small successes over time to generate what are now substantial financial resources created within those closely associated with MCT a significant sense of ownership and empowerment in a multiple set of stakeholders in FSM15. The success factors of the MCT in generating substantial financial resources include: \uf0b7 Maintaining trust \u2013 starting with limited resources required the MCT to prove their ability to manage, disburse and monitor funds carefully. Building this track record required the MCT to be a solid and fully operational organization to expand its area of focus. The MCT has built a strong support team to help evaluate its progress and to provide guidance as well as to suggest adaptive management when necessary. International donors considering giving support to the MCT appreciate that it is managed in light of requirements of the MCT\u2019s donors for transparency and accountability for the spending of all funds provided, and the MCT\u2019s developing track record of success is enhancing donor confidence in its operations and in the projects supported by it. \uf0b7 Serving as a funding mediator \u2013 the MCT developed a capacity to perform what could be described as \u2018funding mediator\u2019 roles. This occurs as MCT is highly cognizant of the economic, cultural, political and ecological landscape in Micronesia and is thus well-placed to decide which initiatives and organizations warrant funding, to efficiently monitor projects and to provide guidance and mentoring to local grantees16. \uf0b7 Building on its comparative advantage \u2013 the MCT will only take on an effort if it will add value to it. 14 Ibid. 15 Ibid., pg. 20 16 Ibid., pg. 24 13 Case Study Report: Micronesian Conservation Trust The advantage of a subregional fund in the Pacific The advantage of operating the fund at a subregional level is the cost-effectiveness and feasibility of having such an entity. Specifically, the Pacific region is one of the most complicated regions because the countries and islands are spread out and logistically difficult for transportation. The Pacific Region is also complex due to the high diversity in culture, resource management and tenure systems. The MCT serving as a subregional financing mechanism for Micronesia makes sense based on the long history of working together. The cultures, long tenure and resource management issues are also quite similar which puts MCT in a good position to address these issues in a culturally sensitive manner. This type of fund can also be suggested for the case of a climate fund or for the Adaptation Fund in the Pacific although assessment considering country specific characteristics is crucial. 14 Case Study Report: Micronesian Conservation Trust Authors: Jorge Gastelumendi, Silvia Irawan, Lisa Schindler, William Kostka, Kevin Petrini, Alex Heikens Cover Photo: Lien Heikens Disclaimer: The views expressed in this publication are those of the authors and do not necessarily represent those of the United Nations, including UNDP, or its member states. Citation: Gastelumendi et al. (2012) Case Study Report: Micronesia Conservation Trust. A joint TNC/UNDP/MCT working paper. http://www.snap-undp.org/elibrary/default.aspx", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "b07fbf23-efd3-44c7-b95c-9bbdd5c4072e": {"__data__": {"id_": "b07fbf23-efd3-44c7-b95c-9bbdd5c4072e", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-tuvalu-trust-fund", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "National Climate Fund Case Study Report: Tuvalu Trust Fund", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-tuvalu-trust-fund", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "06a7c6cf9ff71df2b4e7105f1ae2fafbc0f632cf3ff869f0b6aac41bc2dca365"}, "3": {"node_id": "35bda4b7-f94d-4d81-86c9-6329c5e443fe", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-tuvalu-trust-fund", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "514b5e04f2153456f4bd06b740be64970d2982e88d0266f814ef3b6a1dec562b"}}, "hash": "ff62371f4beed5d174795a6730b018ec652927b77a2ce413b1d1491171f75a6b", "text": "Tuvalu Trust Fund A case study providing inputs to discussions in Asia National Climate Funds, jointly pepared by UNDP and Case Study Report: Trust Fund A case study providing inputs to discussions in Asia-Pacific region on the design and management of , jointly pepared by UNDP and the TTF. Case Study Report: Pacific region on the design and management of 2 Case Study Report: Tuvalu Trust Fund Table of Contents Introduction ................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................. 3 The design of the TTF at a glance ....................................................................................................................................................................................................... 3 The legal status ...................................................................................................................................................................................................................................... 3 The fund\u2019s model .................................................................................................................................................................................................................................. 3 Governing body and beneficiaries ................................................................................................................................................................................................ 6 The establishment of the TTF ............................................................................................................................................................................................................... 7 Lessons learned .......................................................................................................................................................................................................................................... 8 3 Case Study Report: Tuvalu Trust Fund Introduction This paper aims to enrich knowledge sharing about the establishment and management of national climate funds (NCFs), which is organized by the Asia-Pacific Community of Practice on Climate Finance. To provide a technical input to the knowledge sharing, UNDP commissioned seven case studies on existing national funds in the fields of environment, conservation, energy, climate change and development. This paper reports the lessons learned extracted from the establishment and management of the Tuvalu Trust Fund (TTF), which is one of seven national funds across the Asia-Pacific region selected as a case study.1 This report first summarizes the design of the TTF and provides a short description about the establishment and the management of the TTF. The lessons-learned from the establishment and management of the TTF are then presented. The case study analysis involved: literature review to set the scope of the study and in-depth interviews with relevant stakeholders, including the Fund Manager and Staff from the TTF. Prior to finalization, the report has been reviewed by the TTF team and the UNDP Pacific Centre. The design of the TTF at a glance The legal status The establishment of the TTF was marked by the signing of an international agreement between The Tuvalu Government and potential donors. The donors involved at the establishment stage were UK, Australia and New Zealand only. Japan and Korea came in the following year but have since not really increased their contributions into the fund. in Suva on 16 June 1987. The purpose of the Fund (as stated in the International Agreement) is to contribute to the long-term financial viability of Tuvalu by providing an additional source of revenue for recurrent expenses of the Government of Tuvalu. The TTF therefore aims to: \u2022 Assist the Government to achieve greater financial authority in the management of its recurrent budget; \u2022 Enable the Government to maintain and if possible improve existing levels of social infrastructure and services; \u2022 Enhance the capacity of the Government to receive and effectively utilize external capital development and technical assistance; \u2022 Enable the Government to meet long-term maintenance and operating costs of social and economic infrastructure and services; and \u2022 Assist the Government to develop the economy of Tuvalu. The fund\u2019s model The TTF has demonstrated that the Trust Fund concept for support to a national budget can have very positive benefits for a small state that lacks the resources and capacity to develop the economy by itself. The TTF contributes around 20 per cent budget revenues, particularly during the diminishing budgetary aid (absolute and percent revenue). The initial value of the Fund was A$27.1 million contributed by: 1 National funds selected for the case study analysis are: Bhutan Trust Fund for Environmental Conservation, China CMD Fund, Cambodia Climate Change Alliance Trust Fund, Thailand Energy Conservation Promotion Fund, Lao Environmental Protection Fund, Micronesian Conservation Trust and Tuvalu Trust Fund: http://www.snap-undp.org/elibrary/default.aspx 4 Case Study Report: Tuvalu Trust Fund \u2022 Tuvalu A$1.6 million \u2022 Australia A$8.0 million \u2022 New Zealand A$8.3 million \u2022 United Kingdom A$8.5 million \u2022 Japan A$0.7 million \u2022 South Korea A$31,000 Since establishment there have been additional contributions of A$38.6 million: \u2022 Tuvalu A$28.2 million \u2022 Australia A$6.4 million \u2022 New Zealand A$3.2 million \u2022 South Korea A$37,821 In recent years the objectives set by the Board for the fund managers has been to provide a real annual return of 4.5 per cent on the capital.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "35bda4b7-f94d-4d81-86c9-6329c5e443fe": {"__data__": {"id_": "35bda4b7-f94d-4d81-86c9-6329c5e443fe", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-tuvalu-trust-fund", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "National Climate Fund Case Study Report: Tuvalu Trust Fund", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-tuvalu-trust-fund", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "06a7c6cf9ff71df2b4e7105f1ae2fafbc0f632cf3ff869f0b6aac41bc2dca365"}, "2": {"node_id": "b07fbf23-efd3-44c7-b95c-9bbdd5c4072e", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-tuvalu-trust-fund", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "ff62371f4beed5d174795a6730b018ec652927b77a2ce413b1d1491171f75a6b"}}, "hash": "514b5e04f2153456f4bd06b740be64970d2982e88d0266f814ef3b6a1dec562b", "text": "It has grown from its small A$27.1 million (initial contributions from its establishment) in 1987 to a comfortable A$127 million (Maintained Value as at March 2012).2 The TTF has an innovative \u201cbinary trust fund structure.\u201d The binary structure consists of an endowment fund and a revolving fund. Like two management bodies, the two fund accounts work in conjunction to improve the overall efficiency of the fund (Figure 1). A repository for the capital of the Trust Fund is known as the \u201cA Account\u201d. Most of", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "7ccc34e4-3e8b-45c7-afea-86b0e344d775": {"__data__": {"id_": "7ccc34e4-3e8b-45c7-afea-86b0e344d775", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-tuvalu-trust-fund", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "National Climate Fund Case Study Report: Tuvalu Trust Fund", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-tuvalu-trust-fund", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "985bbc9cda77d46f326dfbfb4b624dd20824b332a630411655309b4352849a84"}, "3": {"node_id": "8ffde3a6-129e-4112-bb1f-b5d25259b29c", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-tuvalu-trust-fund", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "280dca79c29a61ad53f75e0b594af6825b770affd314356bbf145feadd95da58"}}, "hash": "a33d2b705be46873d8fb241ed6ce8890b4ef528aaf4c5920975a72f277765586", "text": "the \u2018A Account\u2019 is invested in Australia with asset allocations reflecting the requirements to; (i) maintain the real purchasing power of the Fund; and (ii) provide a regular flow of income to the Government of Tuvalu. By agreement, the value of the \u2018A Account\u2019 must be maintained in real terms (including calculations for inflation and administrative expenses). Only during years when the \u2018A Account\u2019s\u2019 Market Value exceeds the Maintained Value does the Government of Tuvalu receive Trust Fund incomes. When market value exceeds maintained value, the difference is referred to as the \u2018automatic distribution\u201d. This difference is paid into the Second Fund. The Second Fund was established to smooth out trust fund contributions to the recurrent budget and to therefore improve the predictability and consistency of transfers. This revolving \u201cbuffer account\u201d, known as account \u201cB\u201d and later \u201cConsolidated Investment Fund\u201d (CIF) receives funds from the returns or \u201cdisbursements\u201d of \u2018A Account\u2019 and belongs exclusively to the Government of Tuvalu. The \u2018B Account\u2019 holds income distributions from the \u2018A Account\u2019 until funds are needed to be used for the national budget. It therefore serves as a buffer against the volatility of the \u2018A Account\u2019 returns, i.e., during years when there are no returns or low returns. The desired balance to be kept in the \u2018B Account\u2019 is four years projection of no income from the \u2018A Account\u2019. The B Account should keep around 16 per cent of the maintained value with recurrent budget allocations, or around 4 per cent of maintained value annually. This would then give four years of consistent or \u201csmoothed out\u201d contributions to Government revenues. This buffer is designed to provide insurance against revenue shocks inherent in economic cycles. The end of the fiscal year 2010/2011, marked the fourth consecutive year when no distribution could be made to the budget because the Market Value of the fund at AU$115.1 million was less than the real market value of AU$127.5 million; however, because of the CIF account, the government was able to draw almost AU$16 million to support budget over the four year period.3 2 This is calculated to be A$122,946,337.00 Market Value as at 31 March 2012 based on the TTFAC Final Report of May 2012. 3 TTF (2011) Tuvalu Trust Fund and Falekaupule Trust Fund, Opportunities to Contribute to an Innovative Funding Modality for Tuvalu\u2019s National and Community Development 5 Case Study Report: Tuvalu Trust Fund The trust fund model has also provided a conduit through which development partners have been able to provide budget support by making contributions to the CIF which development partners are then drawn-down into the budget over a multi-year period. In a similar manner the main trust fund account has enabled development partners to make additional contributions to the capital of the fund. Figure 1 The model of the Tuvalu Trust Fund In 2007, expenditure including Secretariat charges, bank charges, audit fees and the Management fee amounted to 0.8 percent of the net assets of the Fund. In the period since the Fund began to 30 June 2007, $65.7 million has been made available to the Government which allocated it as follows:4 \u2022 Recurrent Budget expenditure $24.1 million \u2022 Re-invested in the TTF $29.2 million \u2022 Held as a buffer in the B Account $12.4 million Central to the operation of the fund is the requirement that the capital of the fund be maintained in real terms for inflation. Only in very exceptional circumstances would the capital of the fund be considered to be drawn down by the Government of Tuvalu. In the 20 years that the Fund has been operating this has never happened. At the end of each financial year on 30 September, the Advisory Committee calculates the maintained value of the fund based on the Australian Consumer Price Index (CPI). If the market value of the fund is greater than the maintained value, then the difference is automatically distributed to the Tuvalu Government and placed in the CIF. This income is referred to as the automatic distribution from the Fund.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "8ffde3a6-129e-4112-bb1f-b5d25259b29c": {"__data__": {"id_": "8ffde3a6-129e-4112-bb1f-b5d25259b29c", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-tuvalu-trust-fund", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "National Climate Fund Case Study Report: Tuvalu Trust Fund", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-tuvalu-trust-fund", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "985bbc9cda77d46f326dfbfb4b624dd20824b332a630411655309b4352849a84"}, "2": {"node_id": "7ccc34e4-3e8b-45c7-afea-86b0e344d775", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-tuvalu-trust-fund", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "a33d2b705be46873d8fb241ed6ce8890b4ef528aaf4c5920975a72f277765586"}}, "hash": "280dca79c29a61ad53f75e0b594af6825b770affd314356bbf145feadd95da58", "text": "This income is referred to as the automatic distribution from the Fund. If the value of the Fund falls below the Maintained Value then no distribution is made until the Fund once more exceeds its Maintained Value.5 4 TTF (2007) Tuvalu Trust Fund: 20th Anniversary Profile 1987-2007 5 TTF (2007) Tuvalu Trust Fund: 20th Anniversary Profile 1987-2007 6 Case Study Report: Tuvalu Trust Fund Funds drawn down from the CIF into the Government budget are fungible as there is no specific allocation of this revenue to particular classes of expenditure. Unspent balances in the CIF represent Government savings, and may be re-invested in the Fund by returning them to", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "e1c72b5a-832c-4a8b-a71a-0b34f66d30d3": {"__data__": {"id_": "e1c72b5a-832c-4a8b-a71a-0b34f66d30d3", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-tuvalu-trust-fund", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "National Climate Fund Case Study Report: Tuvalu Trust Fund", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-tuvalu-trust-fund", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "3f71992b5e0c2f884388a54ac81bc725ee6f7a36b6602959e1b819fc60bc4f58"}}, "hash": "3f71992b5e0c2f884388a54ac81bc725ee6f7a36b6602959e1b819fc60bc4f58", "text": "the Fund, or carried forward to the next fiscal year. Governing body and beneficiaries The Board of Directors has all powers over the Fund (Figure 2). A Director appointed by the Government of Tuvalu is the Chairman of the Board and one Director appointed by each other original Party to the Agreement. Originally there were four directors with Tuvalu in the chair and the other original parties (Australia, New Zealand and UK) providing members. Following a review of its regional programme in the Pacific, the UK withdrew from the Board in 2004. There is provision for further directors to join the Board and represent any new contributing donors. Japan, Korea ADB and EU have observer status to date. The Board meets twice every year. Professional Fund Managers, two Australian based firms, manage the fund on a day-to-day basis guided by a set of objectives and guidelines established by the Board in accordance with the Articles of the Agreement. At inception the Fund was invested wholly with one \u201cbalanced\u201d Fund Manager. In 1993 the Fund was divided equally among two balanced Fund managers due to diversification considerations. In 2002, coinciding with the appointment of a new Fund Monitor, the Fund undertook a major restructuring by engaging with \u201cspecialist\u201d Fund Managers. Performance of each firm is evaluated independently and comparatively. Professional consultant actuaries evaluate the investment performance of the fund managers based on comparison with other fund managers and provide quarterly reports to the Board of Directors. Currently, monitoring of fund is carried out by Towers Watson (consultant actuaries) that regularly reviews the investment performance of the fund managers and report to the Board on a three monthly basis. In 2005, by a resolution of the Board, an Investment Committee was established to review in detail the reports of the Fund Monitor and make recommendations to the Board on practical steps to be taken. Furthermore, an annual audit is also performed by a professional firm, which is currently Ernst and Young. An Advisory Committee regularly evaluates and monitors the impact of the Fund on Tuvalu and provides economic reports to the Government and the Board. The committee meets bi-annually in Tuvalu for about 10 days. It reviews the Government\u2019s budget and provides advice on macro and micro economic issues. Members of the Advisory Committee consist of one member each representing Australia, New Zealand and the United Kingdom, and Tuvalu. The Secretariat provides ongoing administrative support to the Board of Directors and is based in Funafuti. This role was played by the Secretary of Finance up until 2004 when a fulltime officer was recruited by the Board. Lee Faiva Moresi (TTF Secretary) and Salai Boreham (TTF Assistant Secretary) make up the Secretariat. 7 Case Study Report: Tuvalu Trust Fund Figure 2 Tuvalu trust Fund Governance Structure The establishment of the TTF When Tuvalu achieved independence in 1978 the Government finances were difficult and continued to deteriorate. Unlike Kiribati, Tuvalu did not inherit any financial reserves from the Gilbert and Ellice Islands Colony. In 1982, a preliminary approach was made to the United Kingdom to provide a \u201conce and for all\u201d payment in lieu of continuing direct budget support. This was turned down. A similar approach was made to Australia and New Zealand for \u201cone\u2011off\u201d assistance to reduce the overdraft (estimated at $1.5 million in 1981). This request was also declined and the Government was faced with the prospect of managing the emerging economy on ever reducing finances. By 1984, the Government of Tuvalu had developed the concept of a \u201cReserve Fund\u201d, to which Australia, New Zealand and the United Kingdom might contribute and from which revenues would be used for recurrent expenditure. In January 1985, Tuvalu presented a preliminary paper seeking comments on the concept now described a \u201cspecial budget fund\u201d. This was followed by a further paper, which was discussed with potential donors in Suva in May 1985 that outlined a proposal for a \u201cSpecial Budget\u201d or \u201cTrust Fund\u201d. 8 Case Study Report: Tuvalu Trust Fund In October 1985, Tuvalu provided a more comprehensive submission for the proposed \u201cTuvalu Trust Fund\u201d and this was discussed with various possible donor Governments. Tuvalu\u2019s then Deputy Prime Minister and Minister of Finance visited Australia, New Zealand and the United Kingdom to press the case for the establishment of the Fund. At the meeting with the Prime Minister of New Zealand it was announced that New Zealand had agreed in principle to support the Fund, and would set aside NZ$500,000 in its 1986-87 development assistance budget to be held in reserve pending establishment of the Fund. New Zealand also indicated that it was to", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "0ae0a83e-8b1c-48dc-9a4f-b1f9c594e37c": {"__data__": {"id_": "0ae0a83e-8b1c-48dc-9a4f-b1f9c594e37c", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-tuvalu-trust-fund", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "National Climate Fund Case Study Report: Tuvalu Trust Fund", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-tuvalu-trust-fund", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "bdb7b0807caf19e4b1bb718ef47557327bb3b70e62e16e7be39a7ac009b80789"}}, "hash": "bdb7b0807caf19e4b1bb718ef47557327bb3b70e62e16e7be39a7ac009b80789", "text": "consider providing a further NZ$7,500,000 towards the Fund should other donors (particularly Australia and the United Kingdom) be prepared also to contribute. This was a turning point in the consideration of the proposed Trust Fund. During 1986, New Zealand and the United Kingdom with the support of the United Nations Development Program (UNDP) began to refine the proposal further \u2013 identifying with greater precision the necessary size of the Fund along with the potential legal and other requirements. Australia also undertook its own investigations of possible other alternatives for meeting Tuvalu\u2019s budget difficulties. By mid-1986 regular meetings were being held between Tuvalu Government officials and potential donors with the need to develop a legally binding international agreement. As by now Australia had agreed to support the Fund, having set aside funding within its 1986\u201187 bilateral allocation to Tuvalu, it was important that the negotiations be concluded by June 1987. The agreement establishing the Fund was signed in Suva on 16 June 1987. Lessons learned The Tuvalu has managed to demonstrate comfortably that a Trust Fund set up can have significant positive impacts on national budget and the economy. The TTF has provided Tuvalu with a level of financial security by providing an additional source of government revenue that underpins the Budget and so the whole economy. Although the Fund is not specifically tied to line expenditure items, it is fair to say that real per capita income (on average) and physical infrastructure of Tuvalu have been substantially improved partly due to the Fund\u2019s revenues. Several important lessons from the case of the TFF are: - The model of the TTF - Sequencing the two funds works because it draws on the comparative advantages of both types of funds. The endowment fund is useful for long-term planning and can earn investment income (capital appreciation and dividends); while the revolving fund provides more flexibility when a distribution from the main trust fund is paid. In this respect the two funds can both assist in stabilizing the long-term financial situation of the government as well as addressing short-term budget needs. The challenge of the short-term needs has created much discussion around the size of the CIF, as it balances the objectives of maximizing the drawdowns into the Budget while at the same time maintaining a smooth flow of revenue for the Budget over time. The comparative disadvantages such as more capital upfront and potential to incur investment losses for the trust fund and disruption of resource flows for the revolving fund, balance each other to realize a sustainable funding mechanism for Tuvalu. - Prudent financial management - An important success factor with the TTF has been the prudent approach shown by the government in its financial affairs. This is demonstrated by a discipline to produce balanced or surplus budgets year on year. In its 2007 National Budget, the Government has introduced a TTF Budget Stabilization item in its Multi Year Budget Framework, which is pitched at 4 per cent of the TTF\u2019s maintained value at 30th September of the previous year. This is a major development in the Government\u2019s fiscal management strategies, which to some extent controls the level of drawdowns from the CIF in any given year to a much more sustainable level. The present government is also committed to building the CIF\u2019s capital to reach its Target Minimum Balance (the equivalent of 16 per cent of the TTF\u2019s maintained value) within the next four years. This will ensure the CIF has sufficient capital to provide the sustainable level of buffer to the annual Budget for a period of up to four years. - Strong ownership and relationship with partners - Although there is strict oversight of the TTF, with multiple checks and balances, Tuvalu has a sense of ownership that makes them want to see the fund grow. (In fact, government was criticized by some 9 Case Study Report: Tuvalu Trust Fund for putting off current consumption and reinvesting too much into the fund). Tuvalu is always chair of the board-- important symbolically. Secretariat based in Funafuti with a Tuvaluan in charge of Secretariat responsibilities. Furthermore, appointment of good professional people to the Board and the Advisory Committee who have multiple year terms with staggered completion dates. There is an informal consultative process before people are appointed. Authors: Kevin Petrini, Marilyn Simmons, Silvia Irawan, Alex Heikens Cover Photo: Lien Heikens Acknowledgements: the authors would like to express their gratitude to representatives from the TTF and government, sharing their contributions, comments, views and experiences with the TTF. Disclaimer: The views expressed in this publication are those of the authors and", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": 